WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.040 --> 00:00:03.970
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington D.C.

00:00:19.040 --> 00:00:20.340
&gt;&gt; Elizabeth Peterson:
I'm Betsy Peterson,

00:00:20.340 --> 00:00:22.150
the director of the
American Folklife Center,

00:00:22.150 --> 00:00:26.560
and on behalf of the staff and
everyone in the Library really,

00:00:26.560 --> 00:00:29.110
I'd like to welcome you
to the latest presentation

00:00:29.110 --> 00:00:32.670
of our Benjamin Botkin
lecture series.

00:00:32.670 --> 00:00:37.700
The Botkin series allows
us to highlight the work

00:00:37.700 --> 00:00:41.110
of leading scholars in the
disciplines of folklore,

00:00:41.110 --> 00:00:46.010
ethnomusicology, oral history, and
other cultural heritage studies.

00:00:46.010 --> 00:00:50.760
And it also allows us to
enhance our own collections here.

00:00:50.760 --> 00:00:57.110
All of the lectures that are done
here are videotaped and become part

00:00:57.110 --> 00:01:01.640
of our archival collections and
are later posted as webcasts

00:01:01.640 --> 00:01:03.290
on the Library's website.

00:01:03.290 --> 00:01:06.410
So they're available
for future generations

00:01:06.410 --> 00:01:09.280
and patrons throughout the world.

00:01:09.280 --> 00:01:11.840
So now, if you have a
cellphone turned on,

00:01:11.840 --> 00:01:14.670
please turn it off if you would.

00:01:14.670 --> 00:01:21.830
The American Folklife Center also,
we're delighted when researchers,

00:01:21.830 --> 00:01:24.110 position:56%
of course, make use of our archives.

00:01:24.110 --> 00:01:29.330 position:56%
And many do, and many have published
wonderful books and recordings

00:01:29.330 --> 00:01:32.920
out of the work that they've
done here at the archive.

00:01:32.920 --> 00:01:35.560
But we especially like it
when it brings new insights

00:01:35.560 --> 00:01:40.230
into our materials and when
folks design innovative projects

00:01:40.230 --> 00:01:43.090
and programs based on our holdings.

00:01:43.090 --> 00:01:45.070
And the archive, it
really is the heart

00:01:45.070 --> 00:01:47.230
of the American Folklife Center.

00:01:47.230 --> 00:01:50.630
It's the largest ethnographic
archive in the world.

00:01:50.630 --> 00:01:54.200
And although the word
American is in the title

00:01:54.200 --> 00:01:57.210
of the American Folklife Center,

00:01:57.210 --> 00:01:59.680
that is sometimes a
bit of a misnomer.

00:01:59.680 --> 00:02:04.640
We have collections from over 140
countries throughout the world.

00:02:04.640 --> 00:02:10.540
And in particularly in relation to
our lecture today about Alan Lomax,

00:02:10.540 --> 00:02:14.430
it's also we tend to think
sometimes of Alan Lomax

00:02:14.430 --> 00:02:17.510
as primarily doing work
in the United States,

00:02:17.510 --> 00:02:23.100
and certainly his field recording
trips throughout the south are

00:02:23.100 --> 00:02:27.930
legendary and well-known to many
folks and have been published.

00:02:27.930 --> 00:02:31.520
People have written about, and
many recordings are available.

00:02:31.520 --> 00:02:37.240
But Alan Lomax also did extensive
field work elsewhere in Spain,

00:02:37.240 --> 00:02:41.210
in Italy, in Ireland,
Scotland, and the Caribbean.

00:02:41.210 --> 00:02:45.810
And his 1936 to 37
collecting trip to Haiti

00:02:45.810 --> 00:02:50.920
and his recent reexamination,
reinterpretation and repatriation

00:02:50.920 --> 00:02:55.220
by today's speaker is the
subject of today's talk.

00:02:55.220 --> 00:02:59.430
And we're really thrilled
to have our speaker today.

00:02:59.430 --> 00:03:04.300
And it's my honor to introduce the
distinguished ethnomusicologist,

00:03:04.300 --> 00:03:05.600
Gage Averill.

00:03:05.600 --> 00:03:08.930
Gage is currently dean
of the faulty of arts

00:03:08.930 --> 00:03:10.960
at the University of
British Columbia.

00:03:10.960 --> 00:03:17.130
Formerly, he was vice-principal and
dean of the University of Toronto

00:03:17.130 --> 00:03:21.280
at Mississauga, I hope I said
that right, the dean of music

00:03:21.280 --> 00:03:23.150
at the University of Toronto,

00:03:23.150 --> 00:03:26.730
and the chair of NYU's
department of music.

00:03:26.730 --> 00:03:31.480 position:56%
An ethnomusicologist who specializes
in popular music of the Caribbean

00:03:31.480 --> 00:03:36.330
and North American vernacular
music, Gage has served as president

00:03:36.330 --> 00:03:39.620
of the Society for Ethnomusicology.

00:03:39.620 --> 00:03:45.910 position:56%
