00:06:40.180 --> 00:06:42.960
Haiti has long been
a precarious country.

00:06:42.960 --> 00:06:46.190
Its sovereignty was twice
compromised in the last century

00:06:46.190 --> 00:06:50.680
by the United States
occupations, episodes.

00:06:50.680 --> 00:06:53.550
And I don't want to focus
on the negative here,

00:06:53.550 --> 00:06:59.200
but episodes of political violence
and upheaval, grinding poverty,

00:06:59.200 --> 00:07:03.090
environmental degradation and mass
immigration and natural disasters,

00:07:03.090 --> 00:07:06.270
have taken their toll, not
just on the welfare of Haitians

00:07:06.270 --> 00:07:12.000
and the lives of Haitians but
also on the ability of Haiti

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:16.670
to maintain something like cultural
memory and its cultural heritage.

00:07:16.670 --> 00:07:20.800
During the 29 years of
the Duvalier dictatorship,

00:07:20.800 --> 00:07:25.050
which many of you will be
aware, generations of Haitians

00:07:25.050 --> 00:07:28.340
in the artistic class, in the
intellectual classes, scholars

00:07:28.340 --> 00:07:32.660
and others, left Haiti
to escape oppression.

00:07:32.660 --> 00:07:36.450
And with them went a great
deal of the country's memory,

00:07:36.450 --> 00:07:40.130
great deal of its talent,
its experience.

00:07:40.130 --> 00:07:47.660 position:56%
Following the exiles of the Duvalier
clan, public vengeance took the form

00:07:47.660 --> 00:07:51.690
in many cases [foreign language]
or pulling up of the influence

00:07:51.690 --> 00:07:55.190
of the former dictatorship.

00:07:55.190 --> 00:07:57.600
And that involves some mass
violence and destruction

00:07:57.600 --> 00:08:00.180
of institutions and homes.

00:08:00.180 --> 00:08:04.610 position:56%
Included in that were the [foreign
language] or the Bureau of Ethnology

00:08:04.610 --> 00:08:07.700
in Haiti, which was
the main repository

00:08:07.700 --> 00:08:09.860
