is the van on the right.

00:50:13.130 --> 00:50:15.490
This was the largest
concentration of fatalities.

00:50:15.490 --> 00:50:18.040
It happened in Port-au-Prince,
but of course,

00:50:18.040 --> 00:50:21.050
it extended up to San Mark
and to the north and out

00:50:21.050 --> 00:50:24.740
in the Plateau Central down along
the South Talaogon [phonetic]

00:50:24.740 --> 00:50:27.610
that I've talked about,
which was the center.

00:50:27.610 --> 00:50:30.850
And into Jacmel and
into the south of Haiti.

00:50:30.850 --> 00:50:33.190
Destroyed where the Presidential
Palace, which you'll see

00:50:33.190 --> 00:50:36.740
in a second, the National
Cathedral, National Assembly,

00:50:36.740 --> 00:50:39.220
the Hotel that served as
the base for the MINUSTAH,

00:50:39.220 --> 00:50:43.450
which is the UN stabilization
mission and army barracks.

00:50:43.450 --> 00:50:47.370
And with MINUSTAH and the army
out, effectively out of commission.

00:50:47.370 --> 00:50:49.690
It was up to Haitians to respond

00:50:49.690 --> 00:50:53.080
to the first weeks
after the earthquake.

00:50:53.080 --> 00:50:58.430
I don't want to make this just
an earthquake talk, but you know,

00:50:58.430 --> 00:51:02.570
iconic architecture, cultural
institutions were in rubble.

00:51:02.570 --> 00:51:05.210
Art centers, galleries destroyed.

00:51:05.210 --> 00:51:06.910 position:56%
Artworks, if they weren't destroyed,

00:51:06.910 --> 00:51:09.110
were exposed to the
elements and theft.

00:51:09.110 --> 00:51:11.710
There were aftershocks.

00:51:11.710 --> 00:51:13.170
Concert venues were destroyed.

00:51:13.170 --> 00:51:17.740
Not an exaggeration to say much
of the material culture of Haiti

00:51:17.740 --> 00:51:20.200
in ruins or threatened at the time.

00:51:20.200 --> 00:51:22.080
But there's also the human capital.

00:51:22.080 --> 00:51:25.500
There were artists
living in tent cities.

00:51:25.500 --> 00:51:27.640
The tent cities sprang
up over Haiti.

00:51:27.640 --> 00:51:30.420
You can see on the right a
little improvised tent city.

00:51:30.420 --> 00:51:35.890
On the left, those shacks were
the main highway in Haiti.

00:51:35.890 --> 00:51:37.980
Those doors of those shacks are

00:51:37.980 --> 00:51:42.910
over the curb entering
on to the main highway.

00:51:42.910 --> 00:51:46.710
You can't find a worse place to
try to live or sleep with children.

00:51:46.710 --> 00:51:52.750
But this is what was, what Haiti
looked like in the aftermath.

00:51:52.750 --> 00:51:56.850
Stirrings of reconstruction
here with the university,

00:51:56.850 --> 00:51:58.580
Quisqueya University,
which is being built

00:51:58.580 --> 00:52:02.110
on the ruins up on the hillsides.

00:52:02.110 --> 00:52:07.330
So we went to Haiti, well before we
got to Haiti, there was an effort

00:52:07.330 --> 00:52:12.010
to get our team out
talking about this project.

00:52:12.010 --> 00:52:17.170
I had thought, quite seriously,
that, you know, nothing was going

00:52:17.170 --> 00:52:20.030
to go on with this
project for years.

00:52:20.030 --> 00:52:25.040
We just assume there are other
fish to fry right now in Haiti.

00:52:25.040 --> 00:52:26.930
And there was grief
and shock and need

00:52:26.930 --> 00:52:29.080
to mobilize the global community.

00:52:29.080 --> 00:52:33.000
But the Green Foundation, which had
signed on to support the effort,

00:52:33.000 --> 00:52:34.300
came back and said, you know,

00:52:34.300 --> 00:52:36.940
they were working with
Clinton Foundation.

00:52:36.940 --> 00:52:38.830
Actually, you know,
not quite so much.

00:52:38.830 --> 00:52:41.240
Right now we need this project.

00:52:41.240 --> 00:52:45.480
We need this project as
part of what's going on.

00:52:45.480 --> 00:52:49.450
And so we were put to work.

00:52:49.450 --> 00:52:52.320
They felt that kind of a
antidote to Haiti as a basket case

00:52:52.320 --> 00:52:54.330
and as a recipient
nation was needed.

00:52:54.330 --> 00:52:56.550
They wanted something that
talked about Haiti's strengths

00:52:56.550 --> 00:53:00.810
and its cultural resources and
its history in positive terms.

00:53:00.810 --> 00:53:05.270
So we started to reconceive what
this repatriation plan was going

00:53:05.270 --> 00:53:07.400
to look like.

00:53:07.400 --> 00:53:09.590
We had stories that
we were all involved

00:53:09.590 --> 00:53:12.980
in this kind of coverage of it.

00:53:12.980 --> 00:53:16.290 position:56%
We were asked to choose, I was asked
to choose music for the box set

00:53:16.290 --> 00:53:19.390
so they could do these PSAs
with stars, Naomi Watts

00:53:19.390 --> 00:53:22.020
and Ben Stiller and
people reading them.

00:53:22.020 --> 00:53:25.100
Money was being devoted from this.

00:53:25.100 --> 00:53:28.580
Box sets were being given
away at fundraisers.

00:53:28.580 --> 00:53:33.220
So we started, we flew to Haiti
to carry this on in March.

00:53:33.220 --> 00:53:37.380
It was unlike any flight
to Haiti I've ever been on.

00:53:37.380 --> 00:53:40.620
Usually, it's Haitians
coming back, you know.

00:53:40.620 --> 00:53:46.970
Grannies in Sunday best bringing
boxes of tires for a family.

00:53:46.970 --> 00:53:50.870
This was all North Americans going
down in tee shirts that say Haiti,

00:53:50.870 --> 00:53:55.740
you know, reconstruction,
2010, Baptist church.

00:53:55.740 --> 00:53:58.570 position:56%
It was quite different experiencing.

00:53:58.570 --> 00:54:01.820
You get there, what's usually
a [foreign language], you know,

00:54:01.820 --> 00:54:04.730
you can't get through the traffic,
was just ridiculous, you know.

00:54:04.730 --> 00:54:06.230
The army wasn't out.

00:54:06.230 --> 00:54:10.550
There were cars from all these
relief efforts filling the streets.

00:54:10.550 --> 00:54:15.060
We began the process the next
night after getting in Haiti

00:54:15.060 --> 00:54:18.570
at the Café [foreign language]
which is a cultural center

00:54:18.570 --> 00:54:23.930
which had remained standing, and
its popular performance venue.

00:54:23.930 --> 00:54:26.490 position:56%
The audience, which included
government administers, ambassadors,

00:54:26.490 --> 00:54:30.570
shop owners, musicians,
intellectuals, activists,

00:54:30.570 --> 00:54:32.110
was introduced to the project.

00:54:32.110 --> 00:54:35.010
We had a Vodou jazz band playing.

00:54:35.010 --> 00:54:37.230
We had a panel seen here.

00:54:37.230 --> 00:54:40.920
We've got [foreign name]
cultural activist on the left.

00:54:40.920 --> 00:54:47.470
Joel Widmaier, well-known musician,
radio personality, me, Anna Lomax

00:54:47.470 --> 00:54:51.500
