the project there up on the stage,

00:54:51.500 --> 00:54:54.400
engaging with the audience.

00:54:54.400 --> 00:54:57.190
And I took questions.

00:54:57.190 --> 00:55:00.210
Someone who was there, a
radio DJ out in Leogane,

00:55:00.210 --> 00:55:06.060
decided to organize a Vodou
ceremony with both the Rada,

00:55:06.060 --> 00:55:11.740
you'll see women dressed in
white here, a Rada Vodou society,

00:55:11.740 --> 00:55:15.080
and the Kongo society dressed
in red, coming together

00:55:15.080 --> 00:55:19.170
to welcome these ancestors and
ancestral voices back to Haiti.

00:55:19.170 --> 00:55:24.130
This took place recently,
just after that, in Leogane,

00:55:24.130 --> 00:55:26.470
which had been the
epicenter of the quake.

00:55:26.470 --> 00:55:30.040
Under, you'll see the Mapou
tree, Mapou is the most sacred

00:55:30.040 --> 00:55:33.740
of all trees in Haiti,
conduit of spiritual energy.

00:55:33.740 --> 00:55:37.500
The drums are up against it, but
the ceremony is taking place.

00:55:37.500 --> 00:55:44.990
I just saw that the poster had the
shot, one of these shots on it.

00:55:44.990 --> 00:55:48.250
I played, using a power source
from a, you know, battery,

00:55:48.250 --> 00:55:50.480
built Delco as they
call them in Haiti.

00:55:50.480 --> 00:55:54.230 position:56%
I played songs from the box set
that had been recorded in this area,

00:55:54.230 --> 00:55:59.590
starting with what I expected to
be very well known Vodou pieces.

00:55:59.590 --> 00:56:04.390
And then just started throwing in
these idiosyncratic older songs

00:56:04.390 --> 00:56:08.010
